Starting Table (before all operations)

student_id	name	age	email
1	Ravi	20	ravi@gmail.com
2	Kumar	21	kumar@gmail.com

1️⃣ DROP (Delete a column)

Used to remove a column permanently

Code
ALTER TABLE students
DROP COLUMN email;

Result
Query OK, column dropped

After DROP
| student_id | name  | age |
|------------|-------|-----|
| 1          | Ravi  | 20  |
| 2          | Kumar | 21  |


email column is completely removed ❌

🔄 2️⃣ RENAME (Rename a column)

Used to change column name

Code
ALTER TABLE students
RENAME COLUMN name TO full_name;

Result
Query OK, column renamed

After RENAME

| student_id | full_name | age |
|------------|-----------|-----|
| 1          | Ravi      | 20  |
| 2          | Kumar     | 21  |

Only name changed, data same 


3️⃣ MODIFY (Change column type/size)

Used to change datatype or size

Code
ALTER TABLE students
MODIFY full_name VARCHAR(100);

Result
Query OK, column modified

After MODIFY
full_name changed from VARCHAR(50) → VARCHAR(100)

Data remains unchanged 


Final Difference

Operation	Purpose	Data Impact

DROP	Remove column	Data deleted ❌
RENAME	Change column name	Data safe ✔
MODIFY	Change datatype/size	Data safe ✔

Simple understanding
DROP = 🗑️ Remove
RENAME = 🔄 Rename
MODIFY = ✏️ Change

One-line memory trick

DROP = delete column
RENAME = change name
MODIFY = change structure

Pro Tips
DROP → cannot undo ❌

Always check before:
DESCRIBE students;
